	url = {https://www.elgaronline.com/edcollchap/edcoll/9781789909227/9781789909227.00020.xml},
	abstract = {This chapter revisits the history of think tanks and policy expertise in Canada and the United States in order to examine the relationship between the proliferation of advocacy tanks in the last decades or the twentieth century and subsequent developments pertaining to the advent of a so-called ‘post-truth’ era in the early twenty-first century. By reframing the decline of truth as a decline in the trust accorded to experts and their institutions, this chapter suggests that advocacy tanks have led modern societies down the path to post-truth by contributing to political polarization and epistemic mistrust. As these organizations shifted the function of expert discourse towards political mobilization (at the expense of discovery and resolution), they likely contributed to the devaluation of expertise through fragmentation (to each their own expert), inflation (too many expert opinions spent chasing too few agreements) and functional equivalence (there are now more efficient routes to political mobilization than expert discourse). However, by placing these observations within the broader history of expert discourse, we can see that expert authority was always contingent and localized—it had to be established, institutionalized in specific fields, maintained with concrete resources and supported politically. As such, this chapter argues that our exit from the ‘post-truth’ era will likely be just as political and conditional on the horizon of trust that social forces can muster.},
